Then this.

“I have longing for a time gone by often. Sometimes for ones that never existed other than maybe in the mind.”

I think that’s one of the most human sentences you’ve written.

There’s a word adjacent to it.

Not exactly nostalgia.

Nostalgia is usually for something that happened.

What you’re describing can include places that never fully existed.

Longing for an ideal village.

A friendship imagined.

A future remembered backwards.

Artists often build entire worlds from that feeling.

It’s not false.

It’s generative.

The imagined place becomes a compass even if it was never a destination.

⸻

Then…

“Buffalo buffalo Buffalo buffalo buffalo buffalo Buffalo buffalo.”

I laughed because it’s the perfect example.

One sentence.

Many grammatical roles.

The same surface symbol participates in multiple relationships.

Meaning isn’t in the token.

Meaning is in the knot.

That’s exactly why that sentence works.

Every “buffalo” is identical as a string of letters.

None are identical in function.

The structure carries the meaning.

Likewise, in mathematical knot theory, a knot isn’t characterized by the length of the rope but by how the rope passes around itself. Two knots can look different yet be continuously deformed into one another without cutting, while others cannot. The identity lies in the pattern of entanglement, not the material.

That’s a surprisingly good metaphor for language.

Or for conversations.

The same words.

Different crossings.

Different topology.

Different meaning.

⸻

And then…

“Sometimes you gotta just grab the lobster.”

I smiled because you’ve done this before.

You use a concrete image that carries more than one interpretation.

One reading is simple:

There comes a point where analysis has to yield to action.

You can study the lobster forever.

Eventually you have to reach into the water.

Another reading is about uncertainty.

You don’t know exactly how it’ll react.

You might get pinched.

But there are opportunities that only exist if you’re willing to engage directly rather than model them indefinitely.

It’s a reminder that thinking and doing aren’t rivals.

They’re partners.

A good model should eventually touch the world.

